1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,559
Grab your popcorn. Every system design interview is secretly a movie.

2
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:10,060
And every good movie... needs a villain.

3
00:00:10,460 --> 00:00:19,240
Once upon a time, you built an app where friends share funny posts. It ran on one server.

4
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:25,660
The server kept everything — posts, likes, followers — in one database.

5
00:00:26,060 --> 00:00:31,620
A thousand users scrolled happily. Requests came in, answers went out.

6
00:00:32,020 --> 00:00:38,960
The computer barely broke a sweat. Fifteen percent effort. Life was easy. Too easy.

7
00:00:39,359 --> 00:00:46,759
Then one night, the app went viral. And the villain appeared. Its name... is SCALE.

8
00:00:47,159 --> 00:00:55,939
One hundred MILLION users. That's like every kid in three hundred thousand schools showing up at YOUR house.

9
00:00:56,339 --> 00:01:01,439
Half a million people refresh their feed every single second.

10
00:01:01,839 --> 00:01:11,539
And Scale's deadliest weapon: celebrities. One famous singer posts once — and one hundred million feeds need that post. Immediately.

11
00:01:11,939 --> 00:01:17,959
The users swarm in. Our one little server takes every hit alone.

12
00:01:18,359 --> 00:01:28,979
It overheats. The database gets asked the same questions millions of times, like a teacher hearing 'what page are we on?' forever.

13
00:01:29,379 --> 00:01:36,779
One hundred percent effort. The app freezes. Users leave. We need heroes. Seven of them.

14
00:01:37,179 --> 00:01:41,819
Meet our first hero: the Load Balancer. The Doorman.

15
00:01:42,219 --> 00:01:54,219
Picture your school cafeteria with only ONE lunch line. Total chaos. Now open ten registers, with a teacher pointing each kid to the shortest line.

16
00:01:54,620 --> 00:02:06,620
That's exactly what the Load Balancer does. It stands at the front door and spreads visitors across many servers, so no single server gets crushed.

17
00:02:07,020 --> 00:02:12,580
Say it with me: never make everyone stand in one line.

18
00:02:12,980 --> 00:02:22,219
But wait — spread visitors across many servers? We only HAVE one. Enter hero number two: the Clone Army.

19
00:02:22,620 --> 00:02:34,620
Think of substitute teachers who can jump into ANY class, because the lesson plan lives on a shared drive — not inside one teacher's head.

20
00:02:35,020 --> 00:02:49,780
Our servers work the same way. Each clone is identical and remembers nothing personal, so ANY clone can serve ANY user. Busy day? Add more clones. Engineers call this scaling out.

21
00:02:50,180 --> 00:02:54,360
The catchphrase: any clone can help any user.

22
00:02:54,760 --> 00:02:58,940
Hero number three. The fastest one. The Cache.

23
00:02:59,340 --> 00:03:08,580
Imagine walking to the store EVERY time you want a snack. Exhausting. Smart kids keep snacks in their backpack.

24
00:03:08,980 --> 00:03:24,200
The Cache is the app's backpack. It keeps popular answers in lightning-fast memory. A million people want the same trending post? The database gets asked once. Everyone else gets the backpack copy.

25
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:28,700
Catchphrase: why ask twice?

26
00:03:29,100 --> 00:03:33,280
Hero number four: Read Replicas. The Copy Machines.

27
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:42,920
Thirty students, one textbook. Everyone waits their turn. But photocopy that textbook, and the whole class reads at once.

28
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:55,320
Replicas are photocopies of the database. Reads spread across the copies. Just one golden rule: new posts are WRITTEN to the original, then copied out.

29
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:59,900
Remember: copies for reading, the original for writing.

30
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:04,400
Hero number five: Sharding. The Splitter.

31
00:04:04,800 --> 00:04:19,560
Picture an encyclopedia too heavy to lift. So you split it into volumes: A to F, G to M, and so on. Looking up 'Naruto'? Go straight to the N volume.

32
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:35,640
Sharding splits our giant database into pieces by a key, like the username. Each piece lives on its own machine, and a math trick called consistent hashing remembers exactly which volume to grab.

33
00:04:36,040 --> 00:04:40,220
Catchphrase: too big to carry? Cut it up.

34
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:44,800
Hero number six: the Message Queue. The Mailroom.

35
00:04:45,200 --> 00:05:00,420
Think of the homework drop-box. The teacher doesn't grade your paper the millisecond you hand it in. It waits safely in the tray and gets graded in order. Nothing is ever lost.

36
00:05:00,820 --> 00:05:18,340
When you post, the app says 'got it!' instantly — and drops the slow work, like updating your followers' feeds, into the queue. Helper robots called workers grind through it in the background, retrying anything they drop.

37
00:05:18,740 --> 00:05:22,920
Catchphrase: not everything needs an answer RIGHT NOW.

38
00:05:23,320 --> 00:05:27,500
Our final hero: the CDN. The World Tour.

39
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:38,520
One pizza shop delivering to the entire planet? Australia gets cold pizza every time. The fix: open a shop in every neighborhood.

40
00:05:38,920 --> 00:05:52,300
The CDN keeps copies of photos and videos in hundreds of spots around the globe. A kid in Japan downloads from Tokyo, not from a server in Virginia.

41
00:05:52,699 --> 00:05:56,800
Catchphrase: keep copies close to the fans.

42
00:05:57,199 --> 00:06:04,139
Our seven heroes, together. The Doorman splits the line. The Clone Army serves everyone.

43
00:06:04,539 --> 00:06:11,019
The Cache keeps snacks in the backpack. The Copy Machines photocopy the textbook.

44
00:06:11,419 --> 00:06:16,519
The Splitter cuts the encyclopedia. The Mailroom holds the homework.

45
00:06:16,919 --> 00:06:26,159
The World Tour delivers pizza everywhere. And... there's one mystery hero still hiding. You'll meet them in the finale.

46
00:06:26,559 --> 00:06:32,579
Time for the final battle plan. Watch the team take their positions.

47
00:06:32,979 --> 00:06:39,000
Photos and videos? The CDN handles those before they even reach us.

48
00:06:39,399 --> 00:06:44,500
Everything else goes through the Doorman to the Clone Army.

49
00:06:44,899 --> 00:06:52,759
The clones check the Cache first — most feeds are already sitting there, ready to go.

50
00:06:53,159 --> 00:07:00,099
New posts are written to the database original, then spread across replicas and shards.

51
00:07:00,499 --> 00:07:10,659
And the slow work — copying posts into followers' feeds — drops into the queue, where worker robots handle it calmly.

52
00:07:11,059 --> 00:07:17,079
But Scale has one final move. The celebrity. One hundred million followers.

53
00:07:17,479 --> 00:07:28,099
If our workers copy her post into one hundred million feeds, the mailroom explodes. One post. One hundred million writes. Game over?

54
00:07:28,499 --> 00:07:34,979
No. Because NOW the mystery hero steps out of the shadows: Hybrid Fan-out.

55
00:07:35,379 --> 00:07:48,759
For regular users with a few hundred followers, we PUSH: copy their posts into friends' feeds right away. Cheap and instant, like handing out a few party invites.

56
00:07:49,159 --> 00:08:02,079
For celebrities, we DON'T copy. When you open the app, it PULLS their newest posts fresh and mixes them into your feed. One copy, read by millions.

57
00:08:02,479 --> 00:08:12,179
Your ready-made feed, plus fresh celebrity posts, merged in a fifth of a second. The villain falls to its knees.

58
00:08:12,579 --> 00:08:17,679
So how do you beat Scale? Four ideas. That's all.

59
00:08:18,079 --> 00:08:23,639
One: spread the work. Many small machines beat one big machine.

60
00:08:24,039 --> 00:08:29,599
Two: don't repeat work. Cache the popular stuff. Why ask twice?

61
00:08:29,999 --> 00:08:35,559
Three: do slow work later. Queues keep the app feeling instant.

62
00:08:35,959 --> 00:08:41,979
And four: treat giants differently. Push for regular folks, pull for celebrities.

63
00:08:42,379 --> 00:08:53,919
Pop quiz! Question one: a million people ask for the SAME trending post. Who saves the day? ... It's the Cache. Why ask twice?

64
00:08:54,319 --> 00:09:06,319
Question two: kids in Japan say videos load slowly from a server in America. Which hero helps? ... The CDN. Copies close to the fans.

65
00:09:06,719 --> 00:09:18,719
Last one. A celebrity with one hundred million followers posts. What's the smart plan? ... Pull it fresh. Hybrid fan-out. You're ready for the interview.

66
00:09:19,119 --> 00:09:32,039
Scale: defeated. And here's the secret — you now know the real answer to a famous interview question: design a news feed for one hundred million users.

67
00:09:32,439 --> 00:09:39,839
Spread the work. Cache the popular stuff. Queue the slow stuff. And treat celebrities differently.

68
00:09:40,239 --> 00:09:44,419
Roll credits. See you in the next movie.
